
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `do-release-upgrade` baraye be-rooztar kardan (upgrade) version-e Ubuntu shoma be version-e jadidtar estefade mishavad. In dastoor version-e distro shoma ra check mikonad va be shoma rahnamayi mikonad ta be akharin version beresid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-d`  --> 🚧 Baraye be-rooztar kardan be version-e development (ghabl az release rasmi).  Ehtiat konid!
    🔹 `-f DistUpgradeView`  --> 🖥️ Estefade az GUI baraye namayesh etela'at va gozine-ha.
    🔹 `-m`  --> ⚙️ Force kardan upgrade hata agar chizi dorost kar nemikonad.  Ehtiat konid!
    🔹 `-h`  --> ℹ️ Namayesh komak (help) va rahnamayi dastoor.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ sudo do-release-upgrade

    🔹 Shoru kardan process be-rooztar kardan distro be akharin version-e stable.

    $ sudo do-release-upgrade -d

    🔹 Be-rooztar kardan be version-e development.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ sudo do-release-upgrade

    🔹 Dastoor shoru mishe va version-e system shoma ra check mikonad, bad az shoma soal mikonad ke aya mikhahid be akharin version be-rooz shavid ya na.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `do-release-upgrade` command is used to upgrade your Ubuntu version to a newer release. It checks your distribution version and guides you through the process of upgrading to the latest available release.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-d`  --> 🚧 Upgrade to the development release (pre-release). Use with caution!
    🔹 `-f DistUpgradeView`  --> 🖥️ Use the GUI for displaying information and options during the upgrade.
    🔹 `-m`  --> ⚙️ Force the upgrade even if something seems to be broken. Use with extreme caution!
    🔹 `-h`  --> ℹ️ Display help and usage information for the command.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ sudo do-release-upgrade

    🔹 Starts the distribution upgrade process to the latest stable release.

    $ sudo do-release-upgrade -d

    🔹 Upgrades the system to the development release.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ sudo do-release-upgrade

    🔹 The command starts and checks your system's version, then prompts you to confirm whether you want to upgrade to the latest stable release.
